                    Anorexia nervosa, often referred to simply as anorexia,
                    is a serious and potentially life-threatening eating
                    disorder characterized by an extreme fear of gaining
                    weight and a distorted body image. Individuals with anorexia
                    typically restrict their food intake severely, often to the
                    point of starvation, in an attempt to achieve and
                    maintain an abnormally low body weight.<br />
                    Treatment for anorexia nervosa typically involves
                    a multidisciplinary approach, including medical 
                    management, nutritional counseling, psychotherapy 
                    (such as cognitive-behavioral therapy), and family 
                    therapy. In severe cases, hospitalization or residential 
                    treatment may be necessary to address medical complications 
                    and provide intensive support for recovery.
                </p>
