                    Assertiveness is considered a healthy communication
                    style that can enhance relationships, build self-confidence,
                    and reduce stress. It differs from passivity (where one
                    may fail to express their needs or opinions) and aggression
                    (where one's needs or opinions are expressed in a hostile
                    or disrespectful manner).

                    There are no diseases associated with assertiveness.
                    However, difficulties with assertiveness can contribute
                    to interpersonal problems, low self-esteem, and stress.
                    Fortunately, assertiveness skills can be learned and
                    developed through practice, communication training, and
                    therapy if needed.Assertiveness refers to the ability 
                    to express one's thoughts, feelings, and needs in a direct,
                    honest, and respectful manner
                    and feelings of others.
                </p>

